1) Add defaults to the role
roles/websphere_jvm_restart/defaults/main.yml (ADD)
# Remote temp settings (AIX-friendly)
wsjvm_remote_tmp: "/tmp/.ansible/tmp"
wsjvm_remote_tmp_mode: "1777"
wsjvm_enable_pipelining: true
2) Create a role task to set temp + ensure directory
NEW: roles/websphere_jvm_restart/tasks/setup_remote_tmp.yml
---
- name: Set Ansible remote tmp + pipelining (per-host)
  set_fact:
    ansible_remote_tmp: "{{ wsjvm_remote_tmp }}"
    ansible_ssh_pipelining: "{{ wsjvm_enable_pipelining | bool }}"
  changed_when: false

- name: Ensure Ansible remote tmp directory exists
  file:
    path: "{{ wsjvm_remote_tmp }}"
    state: directory
    mode: "{{ wsjvm_remote_tmp_mode }}"
  become: true

Why this works

ansible_remote_tmp tells Ansible where to create its temp files on that host.
ansible_ssh_pipelining reduces temp file creation.
Directory is created with sticky-bit permissions so it’s safe.
3) Call it at the start of remote execution
roles/websphere_jvm_restart/tasks/execute_on_host.yml (ADD near the top)

Add this after your initial “Initialize per-host tracking” section:

- name: Setup remote tmp for AIX-friendly become operations
  include_tasks: setup_remote_tmp.yml

That ensures every remote host has the temp dir set before you run any stop/start/banner/serverStatus steps.

4) Update file structure
roles/websphere_jvm_restart/tasks/
  setup_remote_tmp.yml   # NEW
Notes / gotchas
This applies per host, so it’s effective even when your AWX inventory is only localhost and you dynamically add hosts.
If your SSH connection user cannot become: true (root) to create /tmp/.ansible/tmp, then create it once manually or pick a directory the SSH user can create (e.g. /tmp/<user>/.ansible/tmp).

If you want, I can also add a guard so the role only runs this on AIX (detected via uname) to avoid unnecessary changes on Linux.
